The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular by bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general director of public relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to enhance the collision prevention capability of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that is very similar to Nissan's Safety Shield.
But most importantly, the bee's compound eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of over 300 degrees in all directions, allow it to fly uninterrupted within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor, which immediately results in collision prevention.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right or greater angle to avoid a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that the evasive maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to prevent collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It requires no storing information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megas".
This is the first step in developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles on the way.
