Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, is the third time that a draft new Constitution has been put to a vote.
Mission accomplished as 64% of the electorate voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results which referred to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" party got 28%, 7%, void and 0,7% blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, he had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a count by an NGO announced a broad "yes" victory, estimating it at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly", he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chavez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in complete calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), were based on a 444-point text that consolidated the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution implies increasing the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially on oil extraction by foreign companies and on foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants reinforced powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms each and has the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50 % of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
19 abductees released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were abducted ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been liberated by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good when they arrived at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an all-terrain safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since moved from one Zulu to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, in charge of organising the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled", said the official, who remained anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "lightning" were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by the secret agents and by members of the Italian special forces.
"We have to recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the secret services, from the special forces", he declared without going into details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The Sudanese army said on the eve of the attack that it had intercepted an all-terrain vehicle carrying the hijackers, killing six of them, including the Chadian chief, and arresting two others.
He also claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Unity Movement (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by this group.
