A debate on the financing of culture has made headlines and is currently dominating the election campaign.
It's better this way.
But one aspect of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums given to the small museums, archives, archaeological digs or national historical sites that are starving?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don't we have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage like in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government is devoting three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Chinon castle in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the American people and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and all of this, in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40 000 benevolent people grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with looking into history, preserving with little money heaps of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
