When, a monument to history and heritage?
The Dutch governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - the first in Europe - will help with the nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in difficulty due to the effects of the mortgage crisis on the North American market: the three countries will support this financial and insurance institution with a total of 11.2 billion euros, which also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held consultations at the highest level with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner responsible for economic competition.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer the euro area crisis in the context of the international financial crisis which has been occurring in several waves for over a year, so the decisions taken with regard to the Bank can in a sense be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken early Sunday morning, the three states will buy about half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including mainly the insurance activities purchased last year from the Dutch ABN Amró.
Fortis' shares started a strong decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too big to allow itself to fail.
The company's stock fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current share prices, the total value of the group's capital on the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to company executives this is not real.
The Bank's management attributed the sharp fall in Fortis' shares to the uncertainties of the North American market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they would not have to worry, they would not lose their money.
The Bank's customers have so far not panicked, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when they see the data on a drug purchase.
Privacy policy experts fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are personal data protection programmes, which link the use of prescription data in all cases to the approval of the person concerned.
It must be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we're leaving the chicken coop to the fox", - quotes the Washington Post from Richard Dick, designer of the medical prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation depend on the health status of the client and if they think the risk is excessive, they just don't make the contract.
They sent the client to a medical check-up and signed the contract with him, knowing the result of the check-up.
Ten years ago Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: with the customer identification number he easily gets from the pharmacies the list of medicines bought in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the client's diseases and health status.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically incurably high, so you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
There are numerous versions of the programme, some even setting a risk number, so that the insurance company has little to do besides the administration, although there are some minor difficulties in this respect.
Among the disadvantages of the programme is that some medicines are multi-use, for example certain substances are used both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies whereas the former is not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities are already forcing them to do this, although they have not received a fine for negligence so far.
Some companies are also now compiling the results of laboratory tests and combining them with data on drug use to obtain more accurate information on the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is becoming more and more difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
The bill giving the authority the right to control companies specialized in the supply of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard recognises that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his programme, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that the person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, after all, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
The overall menu of Marseille
The European Union doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutual trading partners, this issue, along with other largely global issues, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A French-Indian summit will also be held today, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more say in international affairs, the member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This question has not been discussed at the ninth summit which began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Javier Solana, the chief foreign policy official, received Manmohan Singh, the Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade in five years, i.e. to more than 100 billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious target.
The 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India were thus legally harmonised, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is balance, because while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only the ninth trading partner of the Union.
The summit turned its attention to global affairs.
Both sides condemned the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism - in all its forms - and called for the urgent convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha round of trade liberalization was also pressed, although both sides bear a great deal of responsibility for its failure.
The EU confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, i.e. by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least twenty per cent.
India also agrees with this, as at the climate conference next year, a global agreement should be reached and the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also want to prevent the rise in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive contracts worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
