Found the plane of Steve Fossett the millionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane belonging to Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3rd, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris has been found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters in the Mammoth Lakes Nevada Range, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squad, and now we have confirmation that it is the same plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance", he said at a press conference.
The Commissioner has stated that no human remains have been found on or around the plane.
The 63-year-old millionaire was presumed dead in February.
The American Transportation Safety Bureau (TSB) has announced that a few hours after the remains were spotted, a team of investigators was sent to identify the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal remains were found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
It's two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
The search for Fossett had been discontinued a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete a round-the-world flight in a hot air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, I had made the world tour by plane and without stops.
Among his records, there is also that of flying at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
